	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU support helps Fijian farmers reach international markets</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>As sugar loses its traditional role as the country’s main agricultural export, Fiji is seeking to boost output of alternative exports. A World Bank Economic Review has underscored the economic impact of the fall in EU prices and Fiji’s production of sugar. It forecasts that the economy is expected to grow by only about 0.5–1% this year, which is insufficient to fully recover from last year’s 3% fall. Improving upon this performance requires broad economic reform, according to World Bank economist Vikram Nehru. ‘Unless the agriculture and specifically the sugar sector are reformed,’ he is reported as saying, ‘I think we might continue to see long-term growth in Fiji being a significant challenge.’</p><p>UNDP Resident Representative and UN Resident Coordinator Knut Ostby has also emphasised the joint responsibility to support faster development. He has commented, on the one hand, that ‘access to international trade markets is one of many areas where richer countries have to contribute to give room for developing nations. … [and that] richer countries have to increase their development assistance.’ But he has also pointed out that to achieve the desired objectives it is also necessary for ‘developing countries ... to give priority to the [Millennium Development] Goals in their budgets and policies.’</p><p>One alternative (or addition) to sugar is fruits and vegetables (fresh and frozen) and nutraceutical/herbal products such as kava and noni juice. This has been helped by EU-funded technical assistance under the Facilitating Agricultural Commodity Trade (FACT) programme of the Secretariat of the Pacific Community (SPC). FACT’s aim is to sustainably increase quality and range of exports of agriculture and forestry products in and out of the Pacific region. Its pilot project in Fiji, which is EU funded, is due to run for five years with a total budget of €4 million.</p><p>According to Louise Rodan, Export Manager for Balthan (Western) Ltd, Fijian fresh produce is already being sold all over the world. Balthan has received help to improve its production supply chain, including the developing of a Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points (HACCP)-compliant agro-processing facility on Vanua Levu which, despite being Fiji’s second biggest island, is an area where farms have few market outlets. The HACCP unit has enabled Balthan to purchase produce from growers in the northern parts of Fiji.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
