<a href="http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=15674164664cc0c435b16b0102ee9b" target="_self">http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=15674164664c...</a></p><p><i>Fiji Times</i>, ‘Time to compete’, by Reama Biumaiono, 24 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=156658" target="_self">http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=156658</a>&nbsp;</p><p>Facilitating Agriculture Commodity Trade (FACT), website giving details of enterprises participating in the project</p><p>
<a href="http://www.spc.int/lrd/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=438&amp;Itemid=253" target="_self">http://www.spc.int/lrd/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp...</a></p><p>Balthan (Western) Ltd, established in 1975, company’s website home page</p><p>
<a href="http://www.balthan.com/" target="_self">http://www.balthan.com/</a>&nbsp;</p><p>Produce Specialities Ltd (PSL), established in 1998, company’s website home page</p><p>
<a href="http://www.producespec.com/cgi-bin/index.pl" target="_self">http://www.producespec.com/cgi-bin/index.pl</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Fiji’s sugar problems, the result of falls in both prices in the export market and of domestic production, show how vulnerable countries are if they depend on a very small number of exports for foreign exchange and employment. But diversification is hard and needs substantial support over the medium-term, in terms both of external technical and financial assistance and of domestic policy support. The FACT programme shows that when appropriate attention and resources are directed at productivity, value addition and efficiency within the agriculture value chain, the resulting exports can achieve niche marketability and competitiveness on international markets. Balthan (Western) Ltd’s experience in Fiji demonstrates this clearly. The development of the international standards-compliant agro-processing unit has also brought considerable benefits to producer groups, both existing and new growers/suppliers, who, with better market information, are more able to sell their produce and expand production through crop diversification. As well as supplying foreign exchange the move for producer groups from semi-subsistence to commercialised agricultural production has brought about increased returns on labour and management, and enhanced living standards, bringing genuine transformation for stakeholders. The challenge will be in ensuring the longer-term sustainability of these benefits for the stakeholders.</p>
		</div>
		
